.TH HELLO 1 "" "" "User Commands"
.SH NAME
hello \- print a greeting message
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B hello
.RI [ OPTIONS ]
.SH DESCRIPTION
.B hello
is a small command-line program that prints a greeting message to standard
output and exits. The source for this program was recovered from the
.I hello-gcc-O2
binary, originally written in C++ and compiled with gcc at optimization
level
.BR -O2 .
.PP
The implementation lives in a single translation unit,
.IR src/hello.cpp ,
which provides the program entry point together with a helper routine
responsible for emitting the greeting. There are no external dependencies
and no runtime configuration: invoking the program with no arguments
produces its output and terminates.
.SH OPTIONS
.B hello
follows the general invocation form
.RB ` "hello [OPTIONS]" '.
No options are documented for the recovered program; in normal use it is
run with no arguments.
.SH SEE ALSO
.BR cmake (1),
.BR gcc (1)
